text.Taxonomy and naming:
Verticordia mitchelliana was first formally described by Charles Gardner in 1933 from a specimen collected near Bencubbin and the description was published in Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia. The specific epithet (mitchelliana) honours Sir James Mitchell who was Premier of Western Australia at the time.There are two subspecies:

Verticordia mitchelliana C.A.Gardner subsp. mitchelliana which has petals 7–8 mm (0.28–0.31 in) long and staminodes 3–4 mm (0.1–0.2 in)s long;
Verticordia mitchelliana subsp. implexior  A.S.George & M.D.Barrett which has petals 8.5–11 mm (0.3–0.4 in) long and staminodes 4.5–5 mm (0.18–0.20 in)s long.When Alex George reviewed the genus Verticordia in 1991, he placed this species in subgenus Verticordia, section Intricata along with V. monadelpha, and V. pulchella.
